ground_truth:
Yes, you can use a class instead of arrays to represent the items in the table. Here's an example of how you can modify the code to use a class:

```
using System;

class Item
{
 public string Name { get; set; }
 public string Description { get; set; }
 public int Quantity { get; set; }
 public string Size { get; set; }

 public Item(string name, string description, int quantity, string size)
 {
 Name = name;
 Description = description;
 Quantity = quantity;
 Size = size;
 }
}

class Program
{
 static void Main(string[] args)
 {
 Item[] items =
 {
 new Item("Wallet", "Contains identification and emergency cash", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Mobile Phone", "Contains emergency contact information and a charged battery", 1, "Pocket-sized"),
 new Item("Pocket-sized First Aid Kit", "Contains bandages, antiseptic wipes, and pain relievers", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Multitool/Swiss Army Knife", "Has multiple tools for various situations", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Pen and Notepad", "For jotting down notes or reminders", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Hand Sanitizer/Antibacterial Wipes", "For hygiene purposes", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Small Flashlight/Keychain Light", "For emergencies or navigating in the dark", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Pack of Gum/Mints", "For fresh breath", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Small Pack of Tissues/Handkerchief", "For wiping away sweat or cleaning up spills", 1, "Small"),
 new Item("Small Reusable Bag", "For carrying small items or groceries", 1, "Small")
 };

 Console.WriteLine("{0,-30} {1,-50} {2,-10} {3,-10}", "Item Name", "Description", "Quantity", "Size/Weight");

 foreach (var item in items)
 {
 Console.WriteLine("{0,-30} {1,-50} {2,-10} {3,-10}", item.Name, item.Description, item.Quantity, item.Size);
 }
 }
}
```

This code defines a class called `Item` with properties for each column in the table. Then, it creates an array of `Item` objects and populates it with the data from the list. Finally, it uses a `foreach` loop to print out the contents of the array in a formatted table.

