How can we implement the following code in C# to improve the efficiency of our idea?
```
int count = 0;
for (int i = 0; i < myList.Count; i++) {
 if (myList[i] == target) {
 count++;
 }
}
```
Our current implementation is taking too long to execute and we need to optimize it. Any suggestions on how we can improve this code to make it more efficient?

ground_truth:
One way to improve the efficiency of this code is to use a dictionary to store the count of each element in the list. This will allow us to perform the count operation in constant time, rather than linear time. Here's an example implementation in C#:
```
Dictionary countMap = new Dictionary();
foreach (int element in myList) {
 if (countMap.ContainsKey(element)) {
 countMap[element]++;
 } else {
 countMap[element] = 1;
 }
}
int count = countMap.ContainsKey(target) ? countMap[target] : 0;
```
This implementation iterates through the list once and uses a dictionary to keep track of the count of each element. Then, we can retrieve the count of the target element in constant time using the dictionary. This should be much faster than the original implementation for large lists.

