In JavaScript, a callback is a function that is passed as an argument to another function and is executed inside that function. The purpose of a callback is to allow asynchronous code to be executed after a certain task has completed. 

For example, suppose we have a function that fetches data from a server asynchronously:
```javascript
function fetchData(url, callback) {
 // Code to fetch data asynchronously
 // ...
 // When data is ready, call the callback function
 callback(data);
}
```
In this function, the `url` parameter specifies the URL of the data to fetch, and the `callback` parameter is a function that will be executed when the data is available. The `callback` function takes the `data` parameter, which contains the fetched data.

To use this function, we can define our own callback function that will process the fetched data:
```javascript
fetchData('https://example.com/data', function(data) {
 // Do something with the data
});
```
In this example, we pass a callback function as the second argument to `fetchData`. This function will be executed when the data is ready, and it takes the `data` parameter, which contains the fetched data. We can then use this data to do whatever we need to do, such as rendering it on a web page.

Callbacks are an important tool in JavaScript because they allow us to write efficient, non-blocking code that can handle asynchronous tasks. By passing functions as arguments to other functions, we can ensure that our code executes in the correct order and that we don't block the main thread of execution.

