Here's a Java code snippet that sets a reminder for a user:
```
import java.util.Timer;
import java.util.TimerTask;
public class Reminder {
 Timer timer;
 public Reminder(int seconds) {
 timer = new Timer();
 timer.schedule(new RemindTask(), seconds * 1000);
 }
 class RemindTask extends TimerTask {
 public void run() {
 System.out.println("Reminder: Time's up!");
 timer.cancel(); //Terminate the timer thread
 }
 }
 public static void main(String args[]) {
 System.out.println("Setting reminder for 5 seconds...");
 new Reminder(5);
 }
}
```
To incorporate personalized settings for individual users, we can create a table of user-specific settings that is referenced by the code to set reminders accordingly. Here's an example of how this can be done:
```
import java.util.HashMap;
import java.util.Map;
import java.util.Timer;
import java.util.TimerTask;
public class Reminder {
 Timer timer;
 Map settings;
 public Reminder(String user) {
 timer = new Timer();
 settings = new HashMap();
 // Load user-specific settings from a table
 settings.put("user1", 10);
 settings.put("user2", 20);
 settings.put("user3", 30);
 int seconds = settings.get(user);
 timer.schedule(new RemindTask(), seconds * 1000);
 }
 class RemindTask extends TimerTask {
 public void run() {
 System.out.println("Reminder: Time's up!");
 timer.cancel(); //Terminate the timer thread
 }
 }
 public static void main(String args[]) {
 String user = "user1";
 System.out.println("Setting reminder for " + user + "...");
 new Reminder(user);
 }
}
```
In this example, we create a `settings` map that contains user-specific settings. We load these settings from a table (in this case, hardcoded into the code, but in a real-world scenario, this would come from a database or a configuration file). We then use the `get` method of the map to retrieve the user's specific setting and use it to set the reminder. This way, each user can have a personalized reminder setting that meets their specific needs and schedules.

