To expand this simulation to encompass diverse dice shapes, you can modify the `drawDie` function to accept additional arguments that specify the number of sides and the shape of the dice. For example, you could create a separate function for each type of dice (e.g. d4, d6, d8, etc.) and call the appropriate function based on user input.
To calculate the probability of every possible outcome, you can use basic probability principles. For example, the probability of rolling a specific number on a standard six-sided die is 1/6, since there are six equally likely outcomes. The probability of rolling a certain combination of numbers on multiple dice can be calculated by multiplying the probabilities of each individual roll. For example, the probability of rolling a 7 with two six-sided dice is 6/36, or 1/6, since there are six ways to roll a 7 out of 36 possible outcomes.
