ground_truth:
Yes, you can use AJAX to call the Python script from JavaScript and capture its output. Here's an example code that demonstrates this:
```javascript

let date = new Date().toLocaleDateString();
let time = new Date().toLocaleTimeString();
let os = window.navigator.platform;
let pythonVersion = "Python " + window.navigator.appVersion.match(/Python/(d+.d+)/)[1];

// Use AJAX to call Python script and capture output
let xhr = new XMLHttpRequest();
xhr.open("GET", "/path/to/your/python/script.py", true);
xhr.onload = function() {
 if (xhr.status === 200) {
 let output = xhr.responseText;
 document.write(`
 | Date | Time | Operating System | Python Version | Output |
 |------------|----------|------------------|----------------|--------------|
 | ${date} | ${time} | ${os} | ${pythonVersion} | ${output.trim()} |
 `);
 }
};
xhr.send();

```
Replace `/path/to/your/python/script.py` with the actual path to your Python script. The `xhr.responseText` method captures the output of the Python script, which is then passed to the `document.write` method to format it in the table.

